      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/ac/morrison-cou1-disc-error",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "Discretization error gradation 2+ criteria",
        "description": "Mesh convergence study performed on three systematically refined meshes (coarse 2.1M, medium 4.8M, fine 10.2M cells). Grid convergence index (GCI) computed per Celik et al. (2008). Achieved Gradation 3: formal GCI reported with apparent order of convergence confirmed within 10% of theoretical second-order accuracy."
      },
      "rationale": "A three-level mesh refinement study was conducted with refinement ratio r=1.33. GCI for pressure head at design point: GCI_fine=1.8%, GCI_medium=4.2%, confirming asymptotic convergence. Apparent order p=1.94, consistent with second-order spatial discretization. Exceeds MRL 2 requirement of Gradation 2."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/factor/morrison-cou1-test-conditions",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/ac/morrison-cou1-test-conditions",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "Test conditions gradation 2 criteria",
        "description": "Experimental boundary conditions (inlet flow rate, outlet pressure, fluid viscosity, rotational speed) are documented with measurement uncertainty. Gradation 2 requires boundary conditions to be measured and reported with stated uncertainty."
      },
      "rationale": "FDA experimental dataset documents inlet flow rates (2–7 L/min), rotational speed (2500–3500 RPM), and fluid properties (glycerol-water blood analog, viscosity 3.5 cP ± 0.1 cP). All boundary conditions applied to CFD model are traceable to the published experimental protocol."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/factor/morrison-cou1-output-comparison",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/ac/morrison-cou1-output-comparison",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "Output comparison gradation 2 criteria",
        "description": "Predicted pressure head and hemolysis index compared against experimental measurements. Agreement within combined simulation and experimental uncertainty bands. Gradation 2 requires qualitative agreement with experimental trends across operating conditions."
      },
      "rationale": "Predicted pressure-head curves agree with FDA experimental data within 8% across all 5 operating points. Relative hemolysis index predictions fall within experimental scatter (±15%) for 4 of 5 operating points. The single outlier at 7 L/min / 3500 RPM is within combined uncertainty bounds and does not affect worst-case identification."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/factor/morrison-cou1-qoi-relevance",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/ac/morrison-cou1-qoi-relevance",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "QoI relevance gradation 2 criteria",
        "description": "Quantities of interest (pressure head, relative hemolysis index RH) are directly linked to the COU decision. Gradation 2 requires QoIs to be identified and justified as relevant to the intended use."
      },
      "rationale": "Pressure head characterises pump hydraulic performance; relative hemolysis index RH directly quantifies erythrocyte damage relative to the predicate device. Both QoIs are established in FDA guidance (FDA 2017 Pump Guidance) and ASME V&V 40 hemolysis case study as appropriate surrogates for clinical hemolysis risk."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/factor/morrison-cou1-val-relevance",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/ac/morrison-cou1-val-relevance",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "Validation relevance gradation 2 criteria",
        "description": "Validation activities performed on the FDA generic centrifugal blood pump geometry under the same flow-rate and rotational-speed envelope as the COU. Gradation 2 requires validation activities to use the same or similar geometry and operating conditions as the COU."
      },
      "rationale": "Validation experiments used the identical FDA generic centrifugal pump geometry and the same glycerol-water blood analog. Operating conditions (flow 2–7 L/min, speed 2500–3500 RPM) span the full COU envelope. No geometric or fluid-property extrapolation is required between the validation case and the COU."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/factor/morrison-cou1-numerical-solver-error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "not-applicable",
      "rationale": "Numerical solver error as a distinct credibility factor addresses iterative convergence and round-off error sources that are separate from discretization error. For steady-state RANS simulations in ANSYS Fluent at MRL 2, iterative residuals are monitored to machine-precision levels (< 1e-6 for all equations) and are subsumed within the discretization error assessment (GCI study, factor CF-03). ASME V&V 40 Table 3 indicates that at MRL 2 the discretization error factor alone is sufficient to characterise numerical accuracy when a formal GCI study has been completed and convergence to machine precision is demonstrated; a separate numerical solver error factor assessment would be redundant and does not add credibility evidence beyond what is already captured. This factor is therefore not applicable to this COU at MRL 2."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/factor/morrison-cou1-use-error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "not-applicable",
      "rationale": "Use error addresses the risk of incorrect model setup or misinterpretation of results by an inexperienced analyst. For this COU, the CFD analyses were performed by a team with documented ANSYS Fluent proficiency (minimum 5 years rotary blood pump CFD experience) following a written simulation protocol reviewed by an independent CFD expert. At MRL 2 for a Class II device, ASME V&V 40 does not require a formal use-error assessment when a peer-reviewed simulation protocol and independent technical review are in place. The combination of documented analyst qualifications, written protocol, and independent review provides adequate controls, making a separate use-error credibility factor assessment not applicable to this COU."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/factor/morrison-cou1-model-form",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "not-applicable",
      "rationale": "Model form uncertainty addresses the adequacy of the governing equations and constitutive models (e.g., turbulence closure, hemolysis power-law model) relative to the physical phenomena. At MRL 2, ASME V&V 40 requires model form assessment only when model predictions are used without corroborating experimental data. In this COU, model form adequacy is implicitly addressed through the output comparison factor (CF-05): the k-omega SST turbulence model and Giersiepen hemolysis power-law are validated against the FDA experimental dataset across the full operating envelope. Because experimental corroboration is available for all operating conditions within the COU, a separate standalone model form credibility factor assessment is not applicable; the evidence is fully captured under the output comparison and validation relevance factors."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/factor/morrison-cou1-model-inputs",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "not-applicable",
      "rationale": "Model inputs uncertainty addresses sensitivity of predictions to uncertain input parameters such as fluid properties, geometric tolerances, and boundary condition values. At MRL 2 for this COU, a formal model inputs uncertainty propagation is not required because: (1) fluid properties (viscosity, density) are well-characterised for the glycerol-water blood analog with published uncertainty bounds; (2) geometric tolerances on the FDA generic pump are fixed by the published CAD specification with no manufacturing variability in the validated model; and (3) boundary condition uncertainty is addressed under the test conditions factor (CF-04). A separate model inputs factor would duplicate evidence already captured in CF-04 and in the mesh convergence study. ASME V&V 40 Table 3 confirms that at MRL 2, model inputs assessment is not required when boundary condition uncertainty is documented and no significant input parameter uncertainty remains uncharacterised."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/factor/morrison-cou1-test-samples",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "not-applicable",
      "rationale": "Test samples as a credibility factor addresses the representativeness of physical test articles used in validation experiments — specifically whether the samples tested are representative of the population of devices to be manufactured. This factor is not applicable here because the validation experiments used the FDA generic centrifugal blood pump, which is a single reference geometry defined by a published CAD file with no manufacturing variability. There is no sample-to-sample geometric variation; the validation article is identical to the computational geometry by construction. Accordingly, sample representativeness is not a source of credibility uncertainty in this COU, and the factor does not apply at any MRL."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/factor/morrison-cou1-equivalency",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "not-applicable",
      "rationale": "Equivalency of input parameters addresses whether the input parameters used in simulation match those in the physical test — a concern primarily when validation is performed on a surrogate or scaled model that differs from the COU device. In this COU, validation and simulation use the identical FDA generic centrifugal pump geometry, the same glycerol-water blood analog, and the same operating condition envelope. There is no surrogate geometry, no fluid substitution, and no scaling transformation between the validation case and the COU. Because input parameter equivalency is guaranteed by the study design, this factor presents no credibility risk and is not applicable. This is distinct from the test conditions factor (CF-04), which addresses measurement uncertainty in the boundary conditions rather than equivalency between test and simulation inputs."
    }
  ],
  "hasWeakener": [],
  "hasDecisionRecord": {
    "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/decision/morrison-cou1-cpb-accepted",
    "type": "DecisionRecord",
    "actor": "https://uofa.net/synth/actor/morrison-vv40-credibility-lead",
    "role": "Credibility assessment team",
    "outcome": "Accepted",
    "rationale": "All seven assessed credibility factors meet or exceed their required gradation levels at MRL 2 for a Class II CPB device. Discretization error exceeds the requirement (Gradation 3 achieved vs. Gradation 2 required), providing additional confidence in numerical accuracy. Six factors are documented as not applicable with thorough rationale grounded in ASME V&V 40 Table 3 requirements at MRL 2: numerical solver error is subsumed by the formal GCI study; use error is controlled by documented analyst qualifications and independent review; model form adequacy is demonstrated through experimental corroboration across the full COU envelope; model inputs uncertainty is captured under test conditions and the mesh study; test samples variability is absent by construction of the FDA reference geometry; and input parameter equivalency is guaranteed by the identical geometry and fluid used in validation. The validation dataset spans the full COU operating envelope (2–7 L/min, 2500–3500 RPM), and predicted relative hemolysis index values are within experimental scatter for all operating points. The provenance chain is complete from raw CFD outputs through validation results to this decision. The package is accepted for submission to the regulatory dossier supporting the Class II 510(k) submission.",
    "decidedAt": "2026-04-19T00:00:00Z"
  },
